<h2>
    Introduction to Coho Salmon Fishing in the Pacific Northwest
</h2>
<p>
    Coho salmon, also known as silver salmon, are one of the most exciting sportfish in the Pacific Northwest. Known for their aggressive strikes and acrobatic fights, Coho are a favorite among both novice and seasoned anglers. In Oregon, especially near Portland, these fish return in droves during their spawning runs, offering fantastic opportunities for shore and boat fishing.
</p>
<p>
    Coho typically weigh between 6 and 12 pounds, although fish in the 15- to 20-pound range are not uncommon in Oregon’s robust rivers. Their vibrant silver bodies and distinct hooked jaws (kype) make them easy to identify, and their strong upstream battle makes each catch memorable.
</p>
<h2>
    Why Portland, Oregon is a Prime Spot for Coho Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    Portland sits at the intersection of some of the most productive Coho salmon rivers in the state. With easy access to the Columbia River, Clackamas, Sandy, and Willamette Rivers, Portland offers anglers both urban convenience and wild natural beauty. This unique position allows you to be on prime fishing water in under an hour from most parts of the city.
</p>
<p>
    Moreover, Oregon’s commitment to fishery management has helped maintain healthy Coho populations. Hatchery programs and seasonal regulations ensure consistent returns and ample chances for anglers to catch their limit during the open seasons.
</p>
