<h2>
    Top Rivers and Tributaries for Coho Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<h3>
    Columbia River System
</h3>
<p>
    The Columbia River is the highway for Coho salmon entering Oregon from the Pacific. Bank and boat anglers can target Coho in the mainstem, particularly near <strong>Bonneville Dam</strong>, <strong>Multnomah Channel</strong>, and the <strong>mouth of the Sandy River</strong>.
</p>
<p>
    Boat trolling with spinners and hoochies behind flashers is common here. Pay attention to zone-specific regulations as sections of the Columbia open and close at different times.
</p>
<h3>
    Sandy River
</h3>
<p>
    Just 20 miles east of Portland, the Sandy River is a Coho hotspot. Popular access points include <strong>Dabney State Recreation Area</strong>, <strong>Oxbow Park</strong>, and <strong>Cedar Creek</strong>. Anglers often drift eggs or cast spinners, and many fish are caught from shore.
</p>
<p>
    The Sandy runs strong with hatchery Coho, making it ideal for harvest-minded anglers. September and early October are best.
</p>
<h3>
    Clackamas River
</h3>
<p>
    Running through Gladstone and Oregon City, the Clackamas River hosts both hatchery and wild Coho. Bank access is plentiful along <strong>Highway 224</strong>, and boat launches can be found at <strong>Carver</strong> and <strong>Riverside Park</strong>.
</p>
<p>
    The river's deep pools and riffles make it perfect for both fly and spin fishing. September through October is the ideal time here.
</p>
<h3>
    Willamette River
</h3>
<p>
    While not as famous as the Sandy or Clackamas for Coho, the Willamette offers action, especially near its confluence with the Columbia. Urban anglers fish from docks and jetties in <strong>Portland Harbor</strong>, often using spinners and eggs.
</p>
<p>
    This section is best in <strong>late August through September</strong>, when fresh Coho are moving in.
</p>

<h2>
    Fishing Techniques That Work Best for Coho Salmon
</h2>
<h3>
    Bank Fishing Methods
</h3>
<p>
    Coho salmon are aggressive and can be successfully targeted from the riverbank. Here are popular techniques that work near Portland:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Casting Spinners:</strong> Bright-colored spinners like Blue Fox or Mepps (#3 or #4) in pink, orange, or chartreuse are deadly. Cast across the current and retrieve at a moderate pace.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Fishing with Eggs:</strong> Cured salmon eggs suspended with a small corkie or float are a proven Coho catcher. Use light lead and drift through deep pools.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Float Fishing:</strong> Suspending bait or a jig below a float allows you to present your offering at just the right depth. Ideal for slower water like the Sandy or Clackamas.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Make sure to keep your setup light but strong. A 9-10 ft medium-action rod with 10–12 lb test line works well for most bank scenarios.
</p>
<h3>
    Boat Fishing Tactics
</h3>
<p>
    If you have access to a boat, trolling opens up more water and tactics:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Trolling with Flashers and Hoochies:</strong> A flasher combined with a pink or chartreuse hoochie and herring strip is a go-to rig. Troll slowly, especially early in the morning.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Wobbling Plugs:</strong> Kwikfish or MagLips can provoke aggressive strikes, especially when back-trolled through holding water.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tidewater Trolling:</strong> Near the mouths of rivers like the Sandy and Clackamas, tidewater trolling is effective in late summer when Coho are staging.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Boaters should always check local boating regulations and be aware of water levels and flows.
</p>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing for Coho
</h3>
<p>
    Fly anglers are increasingly targeting Coho in Oregon rivers:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Flies:</strong> Try pink, purple, or chartreuse patterns like Egg-sucking Leeches, Clouser Minnows, or Comets.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Presentation:</strong> Strip the fly with short, erratic movements in 2–6 feet of water.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear:</strong> A 7- to 8-weight rod with a sink-tip line works best in fast-moving water.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Fly fishing works best when fish are stacked in riffles or when water clarity is good.
</p>
