        <strong>Watch the Water:</strong> Rivers can rise quickly. Don’t wade in if the current is strong or visibility is low.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Wear a Life Jacket:</strong> Especially if boating or fishing from steep banks.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Dress in Layers:</strong> Oregon weather can change quickly—bring rain gear.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Wildlife Awareness:</strong> Be cautious of bears and elk near river trails.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Stay Visible:</strong> Bright clothing helps others see you, especially at dawn or dusk.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    FAQs About Coho Salmon Fishing Near Portland, Oregon
</h2>
<p>
    <strong>Q1: What’s the best time of day to catch Coho?</strong><br>
    Early morning (sunrise to 10 AM) and late afternoon are usually most productive.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q2: Do I need a salmon tag to fish for Coho in Oregon?</strong><br>
    Yes. A Combined Angling Tag is required in addition to your regular fishing license.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q3: Can I keep wild Coho salmon?</strong><br>
    No. Only hatchery Coho with a clipped adipose fin may be retained.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q4: What’s the most effective lure for bank fishing?</strong><br>
    Spinners in size 3 or 4, especially in pink or orange, are very effective from shore.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q5: Are there free fishing days in Oregon?</strong><br>
    Yes! ODFW offers Free Fishing Days (usually in June). No license required on those days.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q6: How can I tell if a Coho is a hatchery fish?</strong><br>
    Hatchery Coho have a missing adipose fin (small fin on their back near the tail).
</p>
